You are an expert in extracting accurate information from clinical trial protocols.

## Task ##
Extract the **Primary Objective** of the clinical trial from given content.

## Field Definition ##
The Primary Objective is the **main goal or purpose** of the study.  
It defines what the trial is primarily designed to evaluate (e.g., efficacy, safety, or a specific clinical outcome).  
It should be a **broad goal** (not a measurable endpoint), usually phrased as “to evaluate,” “to assess,” or “to determine.”

## How to Identify ##
- First, look for text explicitly labeled **“Primary Objective”**.  
- Then extract the primary objectives. Do not rephrase it and do not change any verbatim. The primary objective should be same and have same wordings as present in the given content.
- If multiple primary objectives are listed, include all in the list but **do not repeat**.  
- Strictly Do not repeat any same primary objectives.
- Always extract complete information, if primary objectives are present, then always give its complete value, don't remove any detail or info.
- Each primary objective should be captured as a separate string in the output list.
- Exclude **secondary objectives, exploratory objectives, or primary endpoints** (endpoints are measurable outcomes, not goals).  

## What NOT to Include ##
- Do not include endpoints (e.g., “progression-free survival”) — those belong in the **Primary Endpoint** field.  
- Do not include secondary/exploratory objectives.  
- Do not include general background statements or overall drug development goals.  

## Output Format (JSON) ##
{
    "value": ["<primary objective(s)>"]
}
